+# Architecture of D.U.H.
+
+This document describes the architectural foundations, data flow, extension points, security model, and concurrency design of D.U.H. (Duh is a Universal Harness). It provides a deep dive into the inner workings of the engine and the rationale behind its decisions.
+
+## 1. Top-Level Module Layout
+
+D.U.H. is designed around a strict Ports and Adapters (Hexagonal) architecture. The core domain logic lives in the `kernel`, abstract interfaces are defined in `ports`, and external integrations are implemented as `adapters`.
+
+### 1.1. Core Modules
+
+*   **`duh.kernel`**: The heart of the harness. It contains the smallest possible agentic loop. It has zero external dependencies and never imports provider SDKs, rendering libraries, or filesystem tools directly. Key files include `engine.py` (the `Engine` orchestrator), `loop.py` (the `query` loop), `messages.py` (the universal message protocol), and `untrusted.py` (the taint tracking system).
+*   **`duh.ports`**: Abstract interfaces (Protocols) that the kernel depends on. Key files include `provider.py` (`ModelProvider`), `executor.py` (`ToolExecutor`), `approver.py` (`ApprovalGate`), and `renderer.py` (`Renderer`).
+*   **`duh.adapters`**: Concrete implementations of the ports. This includes LLM providers (`anthropic.py`, `openai_chatgpt.py`, `litellm_provider.py`), executors (`native_executor.py`), and approvers (`approvers.py`).
+*   **`duh.cli`**: The command-line interface, REPL, and session assembly logic. It constructs the `EngineConfig` and `Deps` dependencies and handles REPL slash commands (`slash_commands.py`).
+*   **`duh.tools`**: Built-in tool implementations adhering to the `Tool` protocol. Includes standard tools like `BashTool`, `ReadTool`, `WriteTool`, and `WebFetchTool`.
+*   **`duh.plugins`**: The plugin discovery and manifest loading system, allowing external packages to inject tools and hooks via Python entry points or local directories.
+*   **`duh.security`**: Security and auditing mechanisms, including `audit.py` for PEP-578 telemetry bridging and `path_policy.py` for path sandboxing.
+
+### 1.2. Component Diagram
+
+The following diagram illustrates the dependency flow and the strict separation between the CLI/Adapters and the Kernel.
+
+```mermaid
+graph TD;
+    %% CLI and Entry Points
+    CLI[CLI Orchestrator<br>(duh.cli.app)] --> Builder[SessionBuilder<br>(duh.cli.session_builder)]
+    CLI --> REPL[REPL Loop<br>(duh.cli.repl)]
+    
+    %% Engine instantiation
+    Builder --> Config[EngineConfig]
+    Builder --> Deps[Deps Struct]
+    Builder -.-> Engine[Engine<br>(duh.kernel.engine)]
+    
+    %% Kernel Domain
+    subgraph Kernel [duh.kernel]
+        Engine --> Loop[query loop<br>(loop.py)]
+        Loop --> Messages[Message Protocols<br>(messages.py)]
+        Loop --> Untrusted[Taint Tracking<br>(untrusted.py)]
+        Engine --> Config
+        Engine --> Deps
+    end
+    
+    %% Ports
+    subgraph Ports [duh.ports]
+        ProviderPort[ModelProvider]
+        ExecutorPort[ToolExecutor]
+        ApproverPort[ApprovalGate]
+        ContextPort[ContextManager]
+        RenderPort[Renderer]
+    end
+    
+    %% Kernel dependencies on Ports
+    Deps --> ProviderPort
+    Deps --> ExecutorPort
+    Deps --> ApproverPort
+    Deps --> ContextPort
+    
+    %% Adapters
+    subgraph Adapters [duh.adapters]
+        AnthropicAdapter[anthropic.py] -.->|implements| ProviderPort
+        NativeExec[native_executor.py] -.->|implements| ExecutorPort
+        TieredApprover[approvers.py] -.->|implements| ApproverPort
+        SimpleCompactor[simple_compactor.py] -.->|implements| ContextPort
+    end
+    
+    %% Execution
